xposed to western culture. This timely account illustrates the ironic and, at times, unsettling experiences of women who enter the spaces and places made accessible through call center work. Visit the author's website at http://www.working-the-nightshift.com and facebook group.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCall centersxEmployeesxIndia. 0aCall centerszIndiaxEmployees. 0aNight workxIndia. 0aNight workzIndia. 0aWomen employeesxSocial conditionsxIndia. 0aWomen employeeszIndiaxSocial conditions. 0aWomenxEmploymentxIndia. 0aWomenxEmploymentzIndia. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxIndia. 0aWomenzIndiaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477550240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804775502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804775502.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles